<chapter xml:id='chap-whats-new'
         xmlns='http://docbook.org/ns/docbook' version='5.0' xml:lang='en'
         xmlns:xsi='http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance'
         xsi:schemaLocation='http://docbook.org/ns/docbook
                             http://docbook.org/xml/5.0/xsd/docbook.xsd'
         xmlns:xlink='http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink'>
 <title>What's New in ${projectName}</title>

 <!-- Alternative for maintenance releases:
 <para>
  ${projectName} ${docTargetVersion} is a maintenance release.
  It does not introduce new features.
 </para>
 -->

 <itemizedlist>
  <para>
   ${projectName} ${docTargetVersion} fixes a number of issues,
   and provides the following additional features.
  </para>

  <listitem>
   <para>TODO: Update for the release</para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
   <para>
    ${projectName} now supports object decorators (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-340"
     >OPENIG-340</link>).
    Decorators allow you to define heap objects that decorate other objects,
    adding the new behavior that the decorator provides.
   </para>

   <para>
    You can now decorate Filters and Handlers with a CaptureDecorator (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-299"
    >OPENIG-299</link>).
   </para>

   <para>
    You can also decorate Filters and Handlers with a TimerDecorator (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-353"
    >OPENIG-353</link>).
   </para>

   <para>
    For detailed information about decorators,
    see the <citetitle>Reference</citetitle> on
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="reference#decorators-conf"
     xlink:role="http://docbook.org/xlink/role/olink"
    ><citetitle>Decorators</citetitle></link>.
   </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
   <para>
    ${projectName} now allows you to inline configuration objects (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-311"
    >OPENIG-311</link>),
    and to omit "config" fields when all values are optional (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-300"
    >OPENIG-300</link>).
   </para>

   <para>
    When you bring an object inline, you no longer need to specify the "name".
   </para>

   <para>
    For example,
    suppose your former <filename>config.json</filename> file looks like this:
   </para>

   <programlisting language="javascript">
{
    "heap": {
        "objects": [
            {
                "name": "Chain",
                "type": "Chain",
                "config": {
                    "filters": [
                        "ReplaceHostFilter"
                    ],
                    "handler": "Router"
                }
            },
            {
                "name": "ReplaceHostFilter",
                "type": "HeaderFilter",
                "config": {
                    "messageType": "REQUEST",
                    "remove": [
                        "host"
                    ],
                    "add": {
                        "host": [
                            "myhost.com"
                        ]
                    }
                }
            },
            {
                "name": "Router",
                "type": "Router",
                "config": {}
            }
        ]
    },
    "handler": "Chain"
}
   </programlisting>

   <para>
    ${projectName} now lets you rewrite
    the <filename>config.json</filename> file like this:
   </para>

   <programlisting language="javascript">
{
    "heap": {
        "objects": [
            {
                "name": "Chain",
                "type": "Chain",
                "config": {
                    "filters": [
                        {
                            "type": "HeaderFilter",
                            "config": {
                                "messageType": "REQUEST",
                                "remove": [
                                    "host"
                                ],
                                "add": {
                                    "host": [
                                        "myhost.com"
                                    ]
                                }
                            }
                        }
                    ],
                    "handler": {
                        "type": "Router"
                    }
                }
            }
        ]
    },
    "handler": "Chain"
}
   </programlisting>

   <para>
    Many examples in the documentation now use inline configurations.
   </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
   <para>
    ${projectName} can now store session information
    in encrypted JSON Web Token (JWT) cookies on the user-agent (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-278"
    >OPENIG-278</link>).
    By default, ${projectName} continues to back session information
    with HttpSession from the container where ${projectName} runs.
   </para>

   <para>
    With this change, you can specify the session storage
    at the global level, or in a particular route configuration.
    For details, see
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="reference#JwtSession"
     xlink:role="http://docbook.org/xlink/role/olink"
    >JwtSession</link>
    and
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="gateway-guide#keystore-for-jwt-encryption"
     xlink:role="http://docbook.org/xlink/role/olink"
    ><citetitle>Setting Up Keys For JWT Encryption</citetitle></link>.
   </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
   <para>
    ${projectName} script configurations can now include arguments (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-240"
    >OPENIG-240</link>).
   </para>
  </listitem>
 </itemizedlist>
 </chapter>
